### Contingency Planning — CP-2, CP-3, CP-9

**Policy layer:** SSP v1.2, CP-2, CP-3, CP-9 control descriptions. Contingency Plan document (POA&M item 001 — currently AT RISK for 90-day deadline).

**Assessment layer:** SAR: CP-9 backup assessed compliant; backup restoration test verified within RTO. CP-2 identified as POA&M item with 90-day condition at authorization.

**Monitoring layer:** Q1 quarterly backup restoration test — RTO 3:47, within 4-hour target but trend toward limit documented. POA&M item M-003 (CP-9 RTO optimization) created. CP-2 AT RISK status reported in Q1 quarterly AO report. Day 79 self-assessment CP-3 retention gap identified — one of two staff members could not describe the downtime procedure.

*What an auditor would see:* The CP-2 condition was established at authorization and is being actively managed — the AO knows it is AT RISK, the ISSO is tracking the milestone status, and the 45-day check-in was used to surface the clinical leadership attendance gap. This is not a hidden problem; it is a documented, escalated, actively managed challenge. An auditor would view this differently than an organization that missed a CP-2 condition deadline and did not notify the AO.

