## What Audit Readiness Is Not

Two common misconceptions worth naming directly:

**Audit readiness is not about achieving a perfect score.** An organization that enters an audit expecting zero findings and viewing any finding as a failure will make two mistakes: they will suppress or hide legitimate gaps to avoid findings, and they will be demoralized by any findings that do emerge. A mature security program expects that a rigorous external assessment will find some gaps — the continuous monitoring program may have missed something, or the assessor will apply a more rigorous interpretation of a control requirement than the ISSO used. The right measure of audit success is not zero findings; it is findings that are genuine surprises (things the organization did not know), not findings that are known gaps that were not disclosed.

**Audit readiness is not about performing compliance for the assessor.** An organization that behaves differently during an assessment than it does during normal operations is performing compliance. Assessors who conduct interviews carefully, compare interview responses across multiple respondents, and test controls rather than accepting configuration screenshots will notice the performance. The most audit-ready state is the one where the organization operates the same way whether an assessor is watching or not — because the evidence trail that accumulates through genuine operations is more coherent and more credible than evidence assembled specifically for audit review.

