## What I Am Still Thinking About

The IR-3 tabletop exercise gap — the most significant pre-audit action item — raises a question about how to structure the exercise to produce maximum value rather than just documentation.

A tabletop exercise that walks through a pre-scripted scenario in a low-pressure setting where everyone already knows the "right answers" produces documentation but does not test genuine readiness. A well-structured tabletop exercise uses an inject-based scenario where participants must make real decisions under simulated time pressure — and includes at least one scenario element that the IRP does not explicitly address, to see how the team handles unanticipated situations.

For OpenMRS, the most valuable tabletop scenario is probably not the most likely scenario (ransomware, patched and documented in the IRP) — it is a scenario the IRP handles incompletely: a GuardDuty HIGH finding indicating active compromise at 2am on a Saturday, when the Health IT Manager is unreachable, the IT Administrator is on call, and the Compliance Officer has never been contacted outside business hours. The scenario tests succession planning in incident response, not just the documented procedure for business-hours incidents.

This kind of scenario produces findings that are genuinely useful — the team discovers that the IRP does not have a clear escalation path when the primary contact is unreachable, or that the IT Administrator does not have the authority to take certain remediation actions without Health IT Manager approval, or that the Compliance Officer does not know the HIPAA breach notification clock starts from when the organization "should have known" regardless of whether the investigation is complete. Those findings are worth documenting and addressing before an actual incident exposes them.

